  "local_port": 45334,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best TED Talks by youth?",
  "response": "TED Talks by youth are incredibly inspiring, as they often showcase fresh perspectives, innovative ideas, and the power of young voices. Here are some of the best TED Talks by young speakers:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Adora Svitak: \"What Adults Can Learn from Kids\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 12  \n   - **Theme:** Adora argues that kids should be taken seriously and that their creativity and bold thinking can inspire adults.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her eloquence and confidence challenge stereotypes about youth.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Richard Turere: \"My Invention That Made Peace with Lions\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 13  \n   - **Theme:** Richard shares how he invented a lion-deterring system to protect his family\u2019s livestock in Kenya.  \n   - **Why Watch?** A powerful example of how young innovators can solve real-world problems.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Maya Penn: \"Meet a Young Entrepreneur, Cartoonist, Designer, Activist...\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 13  \n   - **Theme:** Maya talks about her journey as a young entrepreneur and environmental activist.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her creativity and passion for sustainability are truly inspiring.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Tavi Gevinson: \"A Teen Just Trying to Figure It Out\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 16  \n   - **Theme:** Tavi discusses the complexity of being a teenager and the search for identity.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her honest and relatable perspective resonates with teens and adults alike.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Jack Andraka: \"A Promising Test for Pancreatic Cancer... from a Teenager\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 17  \n   - **Theme:** Jack shares his breakthrough discovery of a low-cost, early-detection test for pancreatic cancer.  \n   - **Why Watch?** His story highlights the potential of young minds in science and innovation.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Malala Yousafzai: \"How One Girl Stood Up for Education and Changed the World\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 17  \n   - **Theme:** Malala speaks about her fight for girls\u2019 education and surviving a Taliban attack.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her courage and advocacy have made her a global symbol of resilience and change.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Gitanjali Rao: \"A Young Scientist's Quest for Clean Water\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 12  \n   - **Theme:** Gitanjali shares her invention to detect lead in drinking water and her approach to solving problems.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her ingenuity and commitment to social impact are inspiring.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Suleika Jaouad: \"How to Connect While Apart\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** Early 20s  \n   - **Theme:** Suleika, a cancer survivor, reflects on the importance of connection during times of isolation.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her wisdom and vulnerability offer a unique perspective on resilience.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Brittany Wenger: \"How I Taught Myself to Code and Built an App for Breast Cancer Diagnosis\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 17  \n   - **Theme:** Brittany shares how she developed an AI-based tool to diagnose breast cancer.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her story demonstrates how coding can be used to make a meaningful impact.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Isabella Teixeira: \"What Can a 14-Year-Old Teach Us About the Environment?\"**  \n   - **Age at Time of Talk:** 14  \n   - **Theme:** Isabella shares her advocacy for environmental conservation and sustainability.  \n   - **Why Watch?** Her passion for the planet is a call to action for all generations.\n\n---\n\nThese talks are not only inspiring but also a testament to the incredible potential of young people to make a difference in the world.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
